        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Down Farnborough Kent</placeName>
                    <date>Dec. 5<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>.</date>
                    <salute>My dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I am much obliged by your note. I will confine myself to the 8 Plates, of which two only shall be coloured.—<ref target="#foot.f1"/> It seems that I have misexpressed myself to make you suppose that M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Sowerby had made for me any “<hi rend="underline">engraved Plates</hi>”; what he has made are some drawings, which would give you a correct idea of the engravings when made.—</p>
<p>I shall be much obliged for the skeleton Plates, &amp; the drawings (if you have these) to be returned to me as soon as convenient to yourself.—</p>
<p>I sh<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>. be particularly obliged if you would inform me, at what period of 1851, my Part will appear;<ref target="#foot.f2"/> pray do not suppose that I shall cause delay, but I want to know as I think it will be more convenient to me not to set to work at the 8 Plates, till I have got through the press the fossil Part, which the Palæontographical Soc. is going to publish. If you will tell me exactly what you wish, I sh<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> be obliged; &amp; allow me to assure you that I am not dilatory, though my health allows me to work but for a very short time daily.</p>
<p>Your’s sincerely, | C. Darwin.</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
                <div type="tnotes">
                    <note xml:id="tnote.n1">3.4 I have] <hi rend="italic">after del</hi> ‘the’</note>
                </div>

        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-1364.xml" resp="#automat">letter to Edwin Lankester, 27 October [1850]</ref>, n. 1.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">The first volume of <hi rend="italic">Living Cirripedia</hi> (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_4837.xml">1851</ref>) was published as number twenty-one of the <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_3945.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Ray Society’s</ref> publications for 1851, although it did not actually appear until 1852.</note>
        </div>        
            
